<h2>TanStack Virtual Adapter</h2>
<p>
    The TanStack Virtual Adapter bridges the <a href="https://tanstack.com/virtual">TanStack Virtual</a>
    library to Web Everything as a provider for the <a href="/blocks/droplist/">Windowed-Collection intent</a>
    (the <code>Windowed</code> behavior). Only a small, fixed window of rows is ever mounted; the adapter
    translates between TanStack's virtualizer and the intent's own window math, so a consumer already driving
    a TanStack <code>Virtualizer</code> can feed the WE surface — and vice-versa — with no component edits.
</p>

<section class="section-card fui-card">
    <h3 id="status">Status</h3>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
        <strong>Proof of concept:</strong> a pure, dependency-free data transform ships in Frontier UI
        (<code>blocks/droplist/tanstackVirtualAdapter.ts</code>), verified for slice + spacer parity against
        the native window math. The full TanStack-backed live runtime wiring (a real <code>Virtualizer</code>
        driving a scroll container) is the deferred slice — the same posture as the XState engine adapter.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="section-card fui-card">
    <h3 id="concept">Concept</h3>
    <p>
        The intent is the lock: whichever producer — the native
        <code>computeScrollWindow</code>/<code>spacerHeights</code> math or an injected TanStack
        <code>Virtualizer</code> — must yield the same mounted <code>[start, end)</code> slice and the same
        top/bottom spacer heights for a scroll offset. The adapter is two pure translations, so TanStack is
        never a build-time dependency (the host injects the virtualizer):
    </p>

    {% highlight "typescript" %}
import {
  virtualItemsToWindow,
  virtualItemsToSpacers,
  toVirtualizerOptions,
} from '@frontierui/blocks/droplist/tanstackVirtualAdapter';

// intent WindowSpec -> the options a host passes to createVirtualizer()
const options = toVirtualizerOptions({ total, itemHeight: 40, overscan: 3 });
const virtualizer = createVirtualizer({ ...options, getScrollElement: () => scrollEl });

// TanStack VirtualItem[] -> the intent's mounted slice + spacer pads
const items = virtualizer.getVirtualItems();
const { start, end } = virtualItemsToWindow(items);
const { top, bottom } = virtualItemsToSpacers(items, virtualizer.getTotalSize());
    {% endhighlight %}

    <p>
        Both the fixed-height (<code>itemHeight</code>) and variable-height (<code>measure</code>) paths of the
        Windowed behavior are covered — the variable path reads each item's real <code>start</code>/<code>size</code>
        so differing row heights stay correct. Because the translation is pure, a consumer can also drive the
        intent with the native math alone and produce an identical <code>VirtualItem[]</code> shape.
    </p>
</section>

